# Implementing LOB Columns in a Memory-Optimized Table
  Memory-optimized tables do not have off-row or large object (LOB) storage (this limitation has been removed in SQL Server 2016 and above - see [Supported Data Types for In-Memory OLTP](../relational-databases/in-memory-oltp/supported-data-types-for-in-memory-oltp.md)), and the row size limit is 8060 bytes. Storing large binary or character string values can be done in two ways:  
  
-   Split the LOB values into multiple rows.  
  
-   Store the LOB values in a disk based table.  
  
 The following example splits a binary LOB value into multiple rows and inserts the rows into a memory-optimized table:  
  
<pre><code>tsql  
create table BlobTable_inmem (  
   BlobId binary(16) not null,  
   SegmentationId int not null,  
   SegmentValue varbinary(8000) not null,  
   CONSTRAINT [PK_BlobTable_inmem] PRIMARY KEY NONCLUSTERED (BlobId, SegmentationId)   
) with (memory_optimized = on)  
go  
  
-- split up and inserts the LOB value   
create proc WriteBlob (  
@BlobId AS BINARY(16),  
@Blob AS VARBINARY(MAX)  
)AS  
BEGIN  
       DECLARE @segmentLength int = 8000  
       DECLARE @blobLength int =   LEN(@Blob);  
       DECLARE @MaxSegment int = CEILING( @blobLength / 1.0 / @segmentLength );  
       DECLARE @i int = 1;  
       DECLARE @segmentValue varbinary(8000) = 0x;
       WHILE @i < (@MaxSegment + 1)  
       BEGIN  
              SET @segmentValue =   
                SUBSTRING(@Blob, ((@i -1)*@segmentLength + 1),@segmentLength );  
              INSERT dbo.BlobTable_inmem VALUES (@BlobId, @i, @segmentValue);  
              SET @i += 1;  
       END      
END  
GO  
  
-- write a blob  
declare @BlobId BINARY(16) = 0x1,  
       @Blob varbinary(max) =   
exec WriteBlob @BlobId, @Blob  
go  
  
-- verify the table contents - there are 3 rows  
select * from BlobTable_inmem  
go  
  
-- reconstruct a single blob  
declare @BlobId BINARY(16) = 0x1,  
       @Blob varbinary(max) = cast('' as varbinary(max))  
  
select @Blob += SegmentValue   
from BlobTable_inmem  
where BlobId = @BlobId  
order by SegmentationId  
  
select @Blob  
go</code></pre>  
  
 Alternatively, you can define a disk-based table for the LOB column(s). Each row in the memory-optimized table would have a corresponding row in the disk-based table with all the LOB values for that row. In the following example, data about employees is stored in a memory-optimized table, while the photo of each employee is stored in a disk-based table.  
  
```tsql  
CREATE TABLE EmployeePhoto (  
EmployeeId int NOT NULL PRIMARY KEY CLUSTERED,  
Photo varbinary(max))  
  
CREATE TABLE Employee (  
EmployeeId int NOT NULL PRIMARY KEY NONCLUSTERED,  
Name varchar(256) NOT NULL  
) WITH (memory_optimized = on)  
go  
  
CREATE PROC Insert_Employee @EmployeeId int, @Name varchar(256), @Photo varbinary(max) AS   
BEGIN  
BEGIN TRAN  
Insert Employee (EmployeeId, Name) values (@EmployeeId, @Name)  
Insert EmployeePhoto (EmployeeId, Photo) values (@EmployeeId, @Photo)  
COMMIT  
END  
```
